      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Manufacturer-supplied verification test suite results reviewed; order-of-accuracy tests for relevant physics modules confirmed.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent verification suite results reviewed for incompressible viscous flow and species transport modules. Second-order spatial accuracy confirmed via manufactured-solution tests documented in the solver theory guide. Code verification level 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for hemolysis index QoI across at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined meshes (4.2 M, 11.7 M, 28.4 M hexahedral cells) were evaluated at the nominal operating point (5 L/min, 3000 RPM). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI of 2.1% for the normalized hemolysis index, confirming discretization error well below the 5% threshold. Discretization error level 3 achieved, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) documented and reproduced in simulation within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Morrison et al. experimental conditions are fully documented: flow rates 2–8 L/min ± 0.05 L/min, rotational speed 2000–3500 RPM ± 10 RPM, 37°C PBS analog, Hct 30%. All boundary conditions reproduced in CFD within stated experimental tolerances. Test conditions level 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., normalized RMS error, Theil U) computed between simulated and experimental hemolysis index values at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Normalized RMS error of 8.3% computed across five operating points for the relative hemolysis index. Theil U statistic of 0.09 confirms good predictive fidelity. All simulated RH values fall within ±15% of experimental measurements. Output comparison level 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The simulated QoIs (hemolysis index, shear stress distribution) directly correspond to the clinical decision metric (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI, normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and derived relative hemolysis index (RH), directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion RH < 1 used for predicate device comparison. Shear stress scalar fields are intermediate QoIs feeding the power-law hemolysis model. Relevance of QoI level 2 confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on geometrically identical or representative device under clinically relevant operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the same geometry as the COU device. Operating conditions span the full clinical range for CPB (2–8 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Fluid analog (PBS + glycerol, Hct 30%) is representative of diluted intraoperative blood. Relevance of validation activities level 2 confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations; mass imbalance < 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to scaled residuals below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and species equations. Global mass imbalance confirmed below 0.005% for all five operating points. Numerical solver error level 2 achieved, exceeding MRL 2 requirement of level 1."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second qualified engineer; boundary condition inputs verified against experimental records.",
      "rationale": "Independent review of simulation setup, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts completed by a second CFD engineer with cardiovascular device experience. No discrepancies identified. Use error level 1 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification provided that the selected turbulence closure and hemolysis power-law model are appropriate for the Reynolds number regime and shear stress magnitudes encountered in the CPB pump.",
      "rationale": "Model form adequacy was evaluated through a qualitative assessment informed by the published literature on CFD hemolysis modeling in rotary blood pumps. The SST k-omega turbulence closure was selected based on its demonstrated performance in transitional and separated flows characteristic of centrifugal pump impeller passages (Re ~ 10^4–10^5). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model has been widely applied and validated for shear stress exposures in the range 10–400 Pa observed in this device. Expert judgment, corroborated by sensitivity studies varying the turbulence model constants, supports the conclusion that model form error does not materially alter the rank ordering of operating points by hemolysis risk. The qualitative nature of this assessment reflects the inherent difficulty of formally grading model form adequacy for complex multi-physics phenomena, and the assessment team determined that the available evidence collectively supports model form acceptability for the stated COU at MRL 2."
    },
    {
